I really like endless forest walks, especially in the fall üçÇüçÅ. Early in the morning, with birds chirping and singing, the forest is just a great place to unwind. But I sure do take my coffee with me ‚òïüç∂

They call this the forest of the dancing trees, because the forest seems to dance through the crooked trees. In the fog and darkness, these trees create a spooky and mysterious ambience üò±. However, when the light hits them it's absolutely magical üåû. Unfortunaly there will not be a white Christmas in the Netherlands, but still I'm looking forward to a beautiful autumn walk like this on Christmas day üçÅüçÇ

Next are some autumn photos closer to home üòÅ. This morning I was an early bird üê¶. Note: normally I'm absolutely not a morning person. I survive mornings on coffee ‚òï. Anyway, I woke up early to photograph the sunrise in the Speulderbos. This is one of the oldest and most beautiful forests in the Netherlands. It was enchanting to see the first rays of the sun in this forest üåû
.
.
.
#dutchwoods #speulderbos #natuurmonumenten #heelnederland_fotografeert #hn_f

A goodbye to Egypt. I had a great time and it sure is a special country with a rich history. The two things I like most were Abu Simbel and the Red Sea. 
The Red Sea was like an aquarium with beautiful coral and many colored fish. It was kinda weird..in the afternoon I was still snorkeling in the sea üêüüê† and in the evening I flew back home ‚úà. Where to next...
.
.
.
#redsea #egypt #safaga #snorkeling #diving #hikingmadman

I was taken by boat to two beautiful scuba diving locations. The first location was Abu Soma Garden. The dive at this spot lasted approximately 36 minutes. After the dive it was lunch time. The chefs had put together a delicious buffet on the boat. After lunch it was time for my second dive in Ras Abu Soma. It was a fairly long dive of 50 minutes. In addition to all the colored fish, I saw a few moray eels, lion fish and some blue spotted stingrays, which was pretty cool.
.
.
.
#egypt #diving #scubadiving #redsea #hikingmadman

The last destination of my Egypt trip was Safaga, a small town by the sea. The first day in Safaga I planned a scuba diving day trip and the second day a snorkeling trip. I couldn't dive for two days because I had to fly back home the last day. The Red Sea is considered one of the world's top scuba diving destinations.¬†The visibility was excellent so I could test my new Go Pro well. .
.
.
.
#scubadiving #snorkeling #redsea #egypt #hikingmadman

Today the temple of Karnak is the largest remaining religious site of the ancient world.These are the massive pillars of the Great Hypostyle Hall in Karnak Temple. The roof of this temple was supported by 134 columns. It's like standing in a forest of stone. The cool thing is that many Pharaohs added inscriptions to these beautiful columns.
.
.
.

The last temple I visited was Karnak in Luxor. This temple is very impressive and a must-see in Egypt. The many buildings were made in honor of Amun-Ra, the god that created the universe. The first time I heard of this place was in the movie the Mummy Returns. After seeing these movies I always wanted to go to Egypt.
This place also featured in the movie Transformers Revenge of the Fallen. I just love visiting movie locations! üé¨
.
.
.

The next destination was The Valley of the Kings which lies on the Nile's west bank near Luxor. The ancient Egyptians built hidden underground mausoleums on this site, which is also known as the "Gateway To The Afterlife". The photo shows the mortuary temple of Hatshepsut, one of ancient Egypt's¬†first female pharaohs. This temple just blends in beautifully with the cliffs behind it.
.
.
.

It had been above 40 degrees celsius for a week in Egypt. To escape the heat I visited the temple of Edfu before 7 am. An additional advantage was that there weren't many tourists. This temple was built at the place where, according to legend, the battle between two gods took place. The falcon god Horus pierced his evil uncle Seth with a spear (lovely familyüòâ). The photo shows the Court of Offerings at the Temple of Edfu. I guess it was a pretty bloody place back in the days..üôÑ
.
.
.

Early in the morning the boat docked at Edfu. I was taken to the temple of this city by a horse-drawn carriage. I don't really like such transfers but walking was too far. The temple of Edfu is one of the largest and best preserved temples in Egypt and was dedicated to Horus, the falcon god.
.
.
.
#egypt #horus #temple #edfu #hikingmadman

Onto the next destination..I slept on a boat for three days and had a room with a view of the Nile river ü§©. It was magical to see the daily life of the Egyptian people along the banks of the Nile from my room. This river truly brings life to the desert landscape üå¥. Many families have been living and fishing on the mighty Nile for thousand of years.
.
.
.
#nile #palmtrees #river #egypt #hikingmadman

After sunset the boat docked at the city of Kom Ombo.This city played an important role in the gold trade in Ancient Egypt. Today the main attraction of this city is the temple of Kom Ombo. It was very special to visit this riverside temple by night. It sometimes gave a spooky impression, which was kinda cool üò±
The Temple of Kom Ombo is very unique because it's the only temple in Egypt that is dedicated to two gods...the Falcon god Horus and the god of crocodiles Sobek üêä.
.
.
.
#komombo #egypt #temple #ancient #hikingmadman

The sunsets in Egypt were so beautiful. The sun was often intensely red. Here I stood on the upper deck of a boat and slowly I saw the sun go down in the Nile. A special moment to cherish üåû
.
.
.

A temple cut into a solid rock in the middle of the desert...that's Abu Simbel. 
This temple has a very cool phenomenon.
On two days of the year (at sunrise) the sunlight falls through the entrance of the temple exactly on three of the four statues in the shrine. The morning sun illuminates the statues of Amon, Ra and Ramses. The only statue that remains in the shadow is the statue of Ptah, the god of darkness.
.
.
.

Abu Simbel has two temples that are cut into a solid rock cliff. The two temples were built on the order of Ramses II, the greatest pharaoh of all time. The beauty of this place is that the temples aren't visible from a distance. From a dirt road you walk around a large rock and then suddenly you stand in front of these gigantic statues.
The photo shows the smaller temple of Hathor and queen Nefertari, the most important wife (he had 200) of pharaoh Ramses II.
.
.
.

I thought this was one of the most beautiful places in Egypt ... Abu Simbel. Actually this place wasn't in the program but afterwards I was so happy that I saw it. I woke up very early (4 am) because it was a three and a half hour drive from Aswan. This place is located near the border of Sudan on the West bank of the Nile. A couple of years ago traveling to Abu Simbel was still done as part of a police convoy due to security concerns. Which is strange because traveling with a convoy makes you an easier target üòÅ. But luckily this was no longer necessary. More of this place to come!
.
.
.

One last photo of my sailtrip on a Felluca. From the boat I saw many birds such as kingfishers that were hunting for fish.
Beforehand I expected to see maybe Nile crocodiles. But since the construction of the Aswan dam, the crocodiles no longer exist in this area. They now only live in Lake Nasser in the south of the country.
.

.

Went to Philae Island by a small motorboat. The temple on this island is dedicated to Isis (the goddess of fertility). Isis was the wife and sister of Osiris.
Osiris was¬†killed by it's brother Seth, who tore the corpse into pieces and scattered them over Egypt. Isis transformed into a huge bird and flew over Egypt. With her vision she was able to find all the pieces of the body and put him back together. Isis used  powerful magic to bring Osiris back to life for a short moment. He couldn't stay in the world of the living because he was dead, but told her she would give birth to a son, Horus (Falcon god), who would take back the throne from Seth and would become protector of the Egpytian people. Happy end after all üòÅ
.

The thing I loved most about Egypt is that it's got so many unsolved mysteries, stories and myths. Like the Sphinx.
A Sphinx was used as a guard in Ancient Egypt. In this case it's guarding the Pyramids. The Sphinx it's true name is "Horus of the Horizon", representing the dawn and the early morning sun üåû. The statue also faces the rising sun. The nose of the Sphinx is missing and it's still unknown how this exactly happened.
.

It was so cool to see the contrast between the modern city and the ancient civilization. To be honest I didn't like Ca√Øro very much, but the pyramids and the sphinx were fantastic.
